Hi, Abri.

As Abri Immelman wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/20/2004 at 20:14:44 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>What do you call the mathematical principle of the following:
>
>a + b + c + d = a x b x c x d
>1.2 + 1.25 + 1.5 + 3.16 = 1.2 x 1.25 x 1.5 x 3.16
>7.11 = 7.11
>
>[Difficulty]
>I came across this phenomenon and didnt know if there is an actual 
>math principle for it.
>
>[Thoughts]
>It doesnt seem to conform to any integer principles. Maybe because of 
>the decimals used?

It doesn't illustrate any general principle; it is just a rather hard
problem, essentially a Diophantine equation (with one solution). One
key to solving it is to express it in terms of cents rather than
dollars, so that you are looking for whole number values for four
variables.

See this page:

  Adding and Multiplying to Get 7.11
  http://mathforum.org/library/drmath/view/55897.html

If you have any further questions, feel free to write back.


- Doctor Peterson, The Math Forum
  <http://mathforum.org/dr.math/>

